{
  "CGAL::Compute_cone_boundaries_2": {
    "kind": "class",
    "name": "CGAL::Compute_cone_boundaries_2",
    "brief": "The functor for computing the directions of cone boundaries with a given cone number and a given initial direction.",
    "detailed": "This computation can be either inexact by simply dividing an approximate $ \\pi $ by the cone number (which is quick), or exact by using roots of polynomials (requiring number types such as CORE::Expr or leda_real , which are slow). The inexact computation is done by the general functor definition, while the exact computation is done by a specialization of this functor. In the construction of cone-based spanners such as Yao graph and Theta graph implemented by this package, this functor is called first to compute the cone boundaries. Of course, this functor can also be used in other applications where the plane needs to be divided into equally-angled cones. Traits_ Must be either CGAL::Exact_predicates_exact_constructions_kernel_with_root_of or CGAL::Exact_predicates_inexact_constructions_kernel .",
    "members": [
      {
        "kind": "typedef",
        "name": "Direction_2",
        "qualified_name": "CGAL::Compute_cone_boundaries_2::Direction_2",
        "brief": "the direction type.",
        "detailed": "",
        "return_type": "Traits::Direction_2",
        "argsstring": "",
        "params": [],
        "file": "CGAL/Compute_cone_boundaries_2.h",
        "line": "67",
        "section": ""
      },
      {
        "kind": "typedef",
        "name": "Transformation",
        "qualified_name": "CGAL::Compute_cone_boundaries_2::Transformation",
        "brief": "",
        "detailed": "",
        "return_type": "Traits::Aff_transformation_2",
        "argsstring": "",
        "params": [],
        "file": "CGAL/Compute_cone_boundaries_2.h",
        "line": "71",
        "section": ""
      },
      {
        "kind": "function",
        "name": "operator()",
        "qualified_name": "CGAL::Compute_cone_boundaries_2::operator()",
        "brief": "The operator().",
        "detailed": "The direction of the first ray can be specified by the parameter initial_direction , which allows the first ray to start at any direction. This operator first places the initial_direction at the position pointed by result . Then, it calculates the remaining directions (cone boundaries) and output them to result in the counterclockwise order. Finally, the past-the-end iterator for the resulting directions is returned. DirectionOutputIterator an OutputIterator with value type Direction_2 . cone_number The number of cones initial_direction The direction of the first ray result The output iterator",
        "return_type": "DirectionOutputIterator",
        "argsstring": "(const unsigned int cone_number, const Direction_2 &initial_direction, DirectionOutputIterator result)",
        "params": [
